---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const title = 'Now';
const description =
  'What Anivar A. Aravind is working on this quarter — engineering leadership, OpenSLM.ai, the Corrigibility framework, and Layer 8.';

const updated = '30 April 2026';
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <article>
    <header>
      <span class="kicker">Now</span>
      <h1>This quarter.</h1>
      <p class="tail">Last updated: {updated}.</p>
    </header>

    <p>
      Enterprise AI transformation work — agentic governance, context and
      memory architectures, production evaluation in regulated environments.
      Boundaries between probabilistic inference and deterministic execution
      are the load-bearing surface; that is where the engineering content has
      moved.
    </p>

    <p>
      OpenSLM.ai — the Open Small Models Accord (v0.2.0) shipped earlier this
      month with the consent-gated Clarity analytics, the founder
      attribution rebalance, and the structured glossary. Next: tooling
      releases that operationalise LWD-R disclosures, and a small-model
      evaluation harness aligned to the accord's ten principles.
    </p>

    <p>
      Corrigibility — Paper&nbsp;I (DPI) is on SSRN at
      <a href="https://doi.org/10.2139/ssrn.6059075">doi.org/10.2139/ssrn.6059075</a>;
      Paper&nbsp;II (EPI) is on Zenodo at
      <a href="https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.19863649">doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.19863649</a>;
      EPI's SSRN DOI pending. The schema repository will land
      <code>SPEC.md</code>, <code>RULES.md</code>, and
      <code>MEASURES.md</code> as part of an appendix-vs-artifact separation
      pass on the DPI paper.
    </p>

    <p>
      Layer 8 — next pieces are on identity infrastructure economics and on
      what corrigibility looks like for federated and continuously-learning
      systems.
    </p>

    <p>
      Selectively advising. Background interviews on request — see
      <a href="/press/">/press/</a>.
    </p>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
